
@Component
----------
@Component is a Spring stereotype annotation used to mark a class as Spring-managed bean.
During component scanning, Spring automatically detects classes annotated with @Component,
creates their objects and registers them in the IoC container, allowing them to be injected
into other beans using dependency injection.

Internal Working
----------------
When Spring starts
1. Scans packages for classes annotated with @Component
2. Creates an object (bean) of that class.
3. Stores it in the Application Context (IoC Container)
4. Makes it available for dependency injection.

Specialized Annotations.
---------------------------
@Component -> Generic Spring bean
@Service -> Business logic layer
@Reposistory -> Data access layer (DAO)
@Controller -> Web/MVC controller

What is the difference between @Component and @Bean
----------------------------------------------------
@Component is class level annotation and @Bean is method level annontation
Marks class as a spring-managed bean , @bean explicitly defines a bean in a configuration class
Automatically discovered via component scanning vs manually created by spring using method
Less control over instantiation, full control over bean creation
Not possible if you cannot modify the source code, Ideal for third-party libraries

@Configuration
public class CloudConfig{
  @Bean
  public AmazonS3Client amazonS3cleint(){ //third party library cannot use @Componnet since we dont own source code
  return new AmazonS3Client();
}
}

@Primary and @Qualifier
-----------------------
When multiple beans of the same type exist in the Spring Container.

@Primary
- Default bean selection
- Used application-wide
- No need to specify at every injection point

@Qualifier
- Explicit bean selection
- Used for a specific injection point
- Overried @Primary

@Qualifier takes precedence over @Primary when both are present.
